text.tspan: – an in silico Evaluation of Assembly Approaches

flowRoot.flowPara: In some lichens, the mutualistic symbiosis is so close, that the participating organisms are no longer able to survive on their own. This interdependence makes them valuable objects to study the genomic consequences of mutualistic relationships. At the same time this close interdependence confounds genomic studies, as the separate sequencing of the participating organisms is not feasible for many closely interacting symbionts. Genome skimming approaches, using a single library with a short insert size, have been used to investigate genomic features of mutualistic organisms, like their metabolic pathways or gene familiy evolution.

Studying processes like gene loss/inactivation or differential selection pressures requires nearly complete draft genomes, but so far there largely has been work assessing prokaryotic metagenomic assemblies. It is still unclear how a eukaryotic species mixture influences different de novo assembly paradigms, such as de Brujin Graph based methods or Overlap Layout Consensus assemblers and how to optimize assembly parameters as k-mer or overlap sizes. To investigate how those paradigms perform on eukaryotic species mixtures, we performed an in silico study based on a lichen system, mimicking a genome skimming study.

flowRoot.flowPara: To simulate data sets as realistically as possible we started our in silico study with a real sequencing experiment on the lichen Lasallia pustulata. Starting from a single Illumina MiSeq run with 15 million 250 bp paired-end reads, we used FLASH to merge overlapping paired-end reads. We fitted a censored Weibull distribution to the observed insert sizes (Figure 1) which was then used for the in silico generation of sequencing data.

For our simulations we used the draft genomes of Cladonia grayi and Asterochloris sp. as template for generating reads. To simplify things we created a single pseudo-chromosome for each of the two genomes by concatenating all scaffolds and removing ambiguous positions. To characterize both genomes we created libraries of repetitive sequences using RepeatScout and identified repeats using RepeatMasker (see Box 1) and created box plots for both genomes (see Figure 2).

Whole Genome Shotgun reads were simulated using ART. As ART does not allow for non-normally distributed insert sizes we simulated reads individually for insert sizes ranging between 250 bp and 664 bp.

flowRoot.flowPara: Already in single species data we see large differences in assembler performance
In mixed species data sets the coverage distribution further inflates differences between the assemblers.
Optimizing the N50 is not a good idea on mixed species data sets, as this can ignore complete genomes.
Assembler performance in our data is not driven by misassemblies.
MIRA needs no excessive parameter tuning and works well over a large range of coverage ratios for the mixed species data sets.

We preliminary annotated the 8,156 L. pustulata genes with Gene Ontology terms using Blast2GO [14]. About 7,500 of our genes could be annotated with GO terms (Figure 6) and 5,000 genes were assigned Enzyme Codes (Figure 7).
In total 11 different data sets with varying coverages for the two genomes were simulated (Table 1):
Two single species data sets only containing reads from Cladonia grayi, and Asterochloris sp. respectively, to evaluate how different assembly programs perform on the both genomes itself.
Furthermore 9 mixed species twin data sets containing varying coverage ratios for the two organisms, going from 9:1 to 1:9 in steps of 1.

flowRoot.flowPara: For Omega, sga, Velvet & MetaVelvet we explore the parameter space (overlap size and k-mer size respectively) and use the maximization of the N50 size as the optimisation criterion.

Figure 3: Assembly results over the 11 data sets. Bars are centered at total assembly length (red lines are reference lengths). Height of the bars shows the NG50 size. For the assemblies with the asterisk the total assembly length was less than 50% of the reference length. A default height was used in those instances.
Figure 6: Comparing the NG50 to the NGA50 to correct for misassemblies. Even when correcting for local misassemblies MIRA outperforms all other assemblers.
The algal data set (0:10) with its low self similarity yields large NG50 values of up to 4 Mbp with the genome skimming approach (Fig. 3, first column).
For the data of the more repetitive fungal genome a maximum NG50 value of only 320 Kbp is assembled (Fig. 3, last column).
While many of the assemblers tested can extend over original contig boundaries on the Asterochloris sp. pseudo-chromosome, this rarely happens for the C. grayi pseudo-chromosome (Fig. 4).
For both data sets MIRA generates the assemblies with the largest NG50 value.

For the mixed species data set this trend continues, with MIRA yielding the largest NG50 size in virtually all cases. In some cases MetaVelvet fails to assemble both reference genomes, yielding only a single genome (Fig 3., Column 1:9 & 2:8)

This is a side effect of the parameter optimisation strategy. By only optimizing for the N50 size, we ended up choosing a k-mer size which bins the k-mers found in the fungal genome with the sequencing errors (see Fig. 5). Due to this the fungal k-mers are not used during the assembly and discarded.

As the NG50 could also be inflated by misassemblies, we checked for the NGA50. This metric does not use the contigs itself, but rather aligned blocks to calculate the NG metric. This does not change the relative ranking of the different assemblers (Fig. 6).
Figure 4: NGx distribution for Asterochloris sp. & C. grayi. In the alga former contig boundaries are assembled while this rarely happens in the fungus.

Figure 5: kmer-coverage frequency. For the k = 151 assembly, which yielded the largest N50, the fungal k-mers are in the low coverage distribution along with the sequencing errors. In case of the k = 51 assembly they form an own distinct peak.
